                      </figure>
        </li>
              <li data-thumb="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo7-150x150.jpg" data-src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo7.jpg" data-responsive="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo7-980x650.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo7.jpg 2560" data-sub-html="#caption-1974289">
          <figure style="height:665px;">
            <div class="image" style="background-image:url('https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo7-980x650.jpg'); background-color:#000"></div>
                          <figcaption id="caption-1974289">
                <span class="icon caption-arrow icon-drop-indicator"></span>
                                  <div class="caption">
                    Simon Phoenix (Wesley Snipes) escapes from cryoprison in the year 2032.                  </div>
                                                  <div class="credit">
                    <span class="icon icon-camera"></span>
                                          Warner Bros.                                      </div>
                              </figcaption>
                      </figure>
        </li>
              <li data-thumb="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo1A-150x150.jpg" data-src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo1A.jpg" data-responsive="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo1A-980x657.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo1A.jpg 2560" data-sub-html="#caption-1974283">
          <figure style="height:665px;">
            <div class="image" style="background-image:url('https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo1A-980x657.jpg'); background-color:#000"></div>
                          <figcaption id="caption-1974283">
                <span class="icon caption-arrow icon-drop-indicator"></span>
                                  <div class="caption">
                    Lt. Lenina Huxley (Sandra Bullock) is a fan-girl when it comes to late 20th century culture.                  </div>
                                                  <div class="credit">
                    <span class="icon icon-camera"></span>
                                          Warner Bros.                                      </div>
                              </figcaption>
                      </figure>
        </li>
              <li data-thumb="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo8-150x150.jpg" data-src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo8.jpg" data-responsive="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo8-980x657.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo8.jpg 2560" data-sub-html="#caption-1974290">
          <figure style="height:665px;">
            <div class="image" style="background-image:url('https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo8-980x657.jpg'); background-color:#000"></div>
                          <figcaption id="caption-1974290">
                <span class="icon caption-arrow icon-drop-indicator"></span>
                                  <div class="caption">
                    The San Angeles police force thinks they've got this—but they're not prepared for a psychopath like Simon Phoenix                  </div>
                                                  <div class="credit">
                    <span class="icon icon-camera"></span>
                                          Warner Bros.                                      </div>
                              </figcaption>
                      </figure>
        </li>
              <li data-thumb="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo2-150x150.jpg" data-src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo2.jpg" data-responsive="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo2-980x665.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo2.jpg 2560" data-sub-html="#caption-1974284">
          <figure style="height:665px;">
            <div class="image" style="background-image:url('https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo2-980x665.jpg'); background-color:#000"></div>
                          <figcaption id="caption-1974284">
                <span class="icon caption-arrow icon-drop-indicator"></span>
                                  <div class="caption">
                    Snipes shows off his killer martial arts moves                  </div>
                                                  <div class="credit">
                    <span class="icon icon-camera"></span>
                                          Warner Bros.                                      </div>
                              </figcaption>
                      </figure>
        </li>
              <li data-thumb="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo5-150x150.jpg" data-src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo5.jpg" data-responsive="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo5-980x649.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo5.jpg 2560" data-sub-html="#caption-1974287">
          <figure style="height:665px;">
            <div class="image" style="background-image:url('https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo5-980x649.jpg'); background-color:#000"></div>
                          <figcaption id="caption-1974287">
                <span class="icon caption-arrow icon-drop-indicator"></span>
                                  <div class="caption">
                    "He doesn't know how to use the seashells."                  </div>
                                                  <div class="credit">
                    <span class="icon icon-camera"></span>
                                          Warner Bros.                                      </div>
                              </figcaption>
                      </figure>
        </li>
              <li data-thumb="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demoB-150x150.jpg" data-src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demoB.jpg" data-responsive="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demoB-980x621.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demoB.jpg 2560" data-sub-html="#caption-1974296">
          <figure style="height:665px;">
            <div class="image" style="background-image:url('https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demoB-980x621.jpg'); background-color:#000"></div>
                          <figcaption id="caption-1974296">
                <span class="icon caption-arrow icon-drop-indicator"></span>
                                  <div class="caption">
                    Spartan finds a solution to the lack of toilet paper: racking up citations for public profanity.                  </div>
                                                  <div class="credit">
                    <span class="icon icon-camera"></span>
                                          Warner Bros.                                      </div>
                              </figcaption>
                      </figure>
        </li>
          </ul>
  </div>

<p><em>Demolition Man</em> topped the box office in its opening weekend and went on to gross $159 million worldwide against its $77 million budget—not a blockbuster hit, but not a colossal failure either. It was widely viewed as a comeback vehicle for Stallone, whose career had flagged somewhat after a string of box office disappointments. (Stallone is currently enjoying yet another "comeback" in the streaming crime drama <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tulsa_King"><em>Tulsa King</em></a>.) Critical reviews were mixed; not everyone was a fan of producer Joel Silver's over-the-top approach to action flicks. But this is the man behind the <em>Lethal Weapon, Die Hard</em>, and <em>The Matrix</em> franchises—now all classics—plus the first two <em>Predator</em> films. Whether you appreciate his extensive <em>oeuvre</em> or not, there's no denying he was a major influence on film in the late 1980s and 1990s.</p>
<p>The fictional future of <em>Demolition Man</em> is one where the Oldies radio station plays jingles from 20th century commercials and where all the restaurants are Taco Bell, which apparently won the "franchise wars." (It was changed to Pizza Hut in the film's European release, because Taco Bell was less well known overseas.) The ultra-processed food served therein isn't even remotely appetizing, but it did inspire the real Taco Bell to recreate the fictional version at the 2018 San Diego Comic-Con for the film's 25th anniversary.</p>
<p>And who can forget the <a href="https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/three-seashells">meme-worthy</a> mysterious three seashells Spartan encounters in the bathroom in lieu of toilet paper? How they work is a running gag that is never explained, but one assumes it's some kind of futuristic bidet. Waters said in <a href="https://www.liveforfilm.com/2018/08/09/whos-he-think-he-is-bo-diddley-an-interview-with-daniel-waters/">a 2018 interview</a> that initially he couldn't figure out a good future restroom concept and started calling his screenwriter friends for ideas. He reached Larry Karaszewski (<em>Ed Wood)</em> when Karaszewski was literally on the toilet and mentioned a bag of seashells on the shelf. "I was like 'seashells! I’m gonna work with that,'” Waters recalled, and the rest is pop culture history.</p>
  <div class="gallery shortcode-gallery gallery-wide">
    <ul>
              <li data-thumb="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo6-150x150.jpg" data-src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo6.jpg" data-responsive="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo6-980x648.jpg 1080, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo6.jpg 2560" data-sub-html="#caption-1974288">
          <figure style="height:668px;">
            <div class="image" style="background-image:url('https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/demo6-980x648.jpg'); background-color:#000"></div>
                          <figcaption id="caption-1974288">
                <span class="icon caption-arrow icon-drop-indicator"></span>
